{"title_page": "R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name                = R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden\n| native_name         = \n| image               = R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden 01.jpg\n| image_alt           = \n| caption             = \n| former_names        = \n| alternate_names     =\n| map_type            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = English Cottage style\n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[R\u00e5geleje]]\n| client              = \n| owner               =\n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| location_country    = [[Denmark]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|56|6|21.92|N|12|10|42.64|E|type:landmark_region:DK|display=inline,title}}\n| altitude            = \n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = 1915\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = \n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| url                 = \n| references          = \n}}\n'''R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden''' is an [[Arts & Crafts]] inspired country house from 1915 situated on the eastern outskirts of [[R\u00e5geleje]], [[Gribskov Municipality]], some fifty kilometres northwest of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. The house is perched on a small wooded hill, overlooking the  [[Kattegat]] coast. It was listed on the [[Listed buildings in Gribskov Municipality|Danish registry of protected buildings and places]] in 1989. The scope of the heritage listing was expanded in 2012.\n\n==History==\n===Henri Odewahn===\n[[File:R\u00e5geleje by Franz \u0160ediv\u00fd - R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden detail.png|thumb|left|R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden seen on a detail from a [[bird's-eye view]] drawing by [[Franz \u0160ediv\u00fd (illustrator)|Franz \u0160ediv\u00fd]], 1915]]\nHenri Odewahn, one of the owners of C. J. Car\u00f8e, a leading Danish importer of tea and spices, purchased a 7 hectares piece of land at the site in 1914.<ref name=\"arkiv\">{{cite web|url=https://arkiv.dk/vis/5103712|title=R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden, R\u00e5geleje |language=Danish|website=arkiv.dk|accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> A  country house designed by [[Povl Baumann]] was completed on the property the following year.<ref name=\"Kulturstyrelsen\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kulturarv.dk/fbb/sagvis.pub?sag=5693629|title=Sag: R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden|language=Danish|publisher=Kulturstyrelsen|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> Based at [[Niels Brock House|Strandgade 36]] in [[Copenhagen]],<ref name=\"coneliand\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coneliand.dk/Danmarks%20aeldste%20forretninger/Side%20088%20Caroe%20-%20Cent.html|title=C. J. Car\u00f8e|language=Danish|website=coneliand.dk|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> C. J. Car\u00f8e's Cingalla Tea was one of the leading tea brands on the Danish market at the time.<ref name=\"Kulturstyrelsen\"/> In 1907, Odewahn had also established a brand of cherry liqeur under his own name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antikflasker.dk/19512340|title=Dokumentation - en del af min hobby |language=Danish|website=antikflasker.dk|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> He purchased the property at [[Ny Kongensgade 3]] in 1917 but only kept it for four years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kulturarv.dk/fbb/sagvis.pub?sag=3102731|title=Sag: Ny Kongensgade 3 |language=Danish|website=Kulturstyrelsen|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Carl and Frethe Glad===\n[[File:R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden vintage photo.jpg|thumb|R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden]]\nThe property was in the beginning of the 1920s acquired by Carl F. Glad (1890-1977) and his wife Grethe Glad (1891-1990). Glad was the owner of L.C. Glad og Co. and appointed as Austrian consul-general in 1921. He planted the property with flowers and other plants from [[Siberia]].  The Glad's lived at [[Store Mariendal]] in [[Hellerup]]. The Glad's belonged to Copenhagen's high society and were often featured in magazines. They covered the distance between Storee Mariendal and R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden in their [[Isotta Fraschini Tipo 8A|Isotta Fraschini Tipo 8A 1925-26]]. Glad was also the owner of a  [[Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft|Daimler]], [[Bugatti]] and a [[Humber Limited|Humber]].<ref name=\"dvk-database\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dvk-database.dk/bht/bht_1990/bht_1990_101/bht101_1990_38.htm|title=32SG|language=Danish|website=dvk-database.dk|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nGlad's firm went bankrupt in connection with the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|Great Crash of 1929]]. They had to sell both their properties and moved into an apartment in Bredgade. Grethe Glad started the [[Scandinavian Academy of Fashion Design|Margrethe School]] in 1931. After Carl Glad had successfully revived his business a few years later, they were in 1937 able to purchase a property at [[Frederiksholms Kanal]] and to reacquire R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden.<ref name=\"kvinfo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kvinfo.dk/side/597/bio/940/origin/170/|title=Grethe Glad (1891 - 1990)|language=Danish|website=kvinfo.dk|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> Glad was also involved in the Toro Oil Corporation Denmark Limited A/S at [[L\u00f8ve House|Bredgade 76]]. Glad kept the Isotta Fraschini until the early 1970s when  it was then sold to his R\u00e5geleje neighbors Rita and Erik Orth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://veteranbilklub.dk/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/403-VT-januar-2010-lavopl.pdf|title=Aarhus-K\u00f8benhavn maj 1972|language=Danish|website=Veteran Tidende|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"dvk-database\"/>\n\n===Later history===\nGlad sold R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden to the government in 1973. Sten Bramsen, a [[DR (broadcaster)|DR]] producer and president of Musikalske Venners Fond, took a 10-year lease on the property in the late 1970s with the intention of operating it as a music venue but the lease was terminated prematurely after just two years.<ref name=\"danskefilm\">{{cite web|url=https://danskefilm.dk/lokation.php?id=89|title=R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden|language=Danish|website=danskfilm.dk|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nR\u00e5geg\u00e5rden was in 1981 let out to Martin Christensen, Djon Andersen and Ingrid Andersen. They used it as a combined art exhibition venue and antique shop.\n\n==Architecture==\nThe property consists of a three winged main building, an L-shaped garage and stable and a small octagonal well house. The main building is designed in English cottage style with clear inspiration from the [[Arts & Crafts movement]] and [[Baillie Scott]].<ref name=\"Kulturstyrelsen\"/>\n\n==Today==\nR\u00e5geg\u00e5rden is now owned by UK-based [[CVC Capital Partners|CVC]] partner S\u00f8ren Vestergaard-Poulsen, The surrounding woodland, locally referred to as Glads Have (Glad's Garden), is still owned by the Danish Nature Agency.<ref name=\"danskefilm\"/>\n\n==Cultural references==\nMost of the 1964 thriller ''[[D\u00f8den kommer til middag]]'' was shot in and around R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden.<ref name=\"danskefilm\"/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=180px>\nImage:R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden 03.jpg|The main building seen from the driveway\nImage:R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden 06.jpg|The facade towards the water\nFile:R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden 08.jpg|The main building seen from the west\nImage:R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden 02.jpg|South side of the main building\nImage:R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden - staldl\u00e6nge 02.jpg|The stable wing\nImage:R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden - staldl\u00e6nge 03.jpg|The well house and the stable\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mikkelborg, H\u00f8rsholm#Mikkelg\u00e5rd|Mikkelg\u00e5rd]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.familiesporet.dk/pgv/note.php?nid=N8222&ged=Correll_Dohlmann.ged Source]\n* [http://www.dvk-database.dk/bht/bht_1990/bht_1990_101/bht101_1990_38.htm Source]\n* [https://www.biografmuseet.dk/nyheder/2017/constantin/index.htm Source]\n* [http://liselejeqr.dk/hyllingebjerghus/ Source]\n\n{{Gribskov Municipality}}\n\n[[Category:Listed buildings and structures in Gribskov Municipality]]\n[[Category:Listed residential buildings in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Houses in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1915]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name                = R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden\n| native_name         = \n| image               = R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden 01.jpg\n| image_alt           = \n| caption             = \n| former_names        = \n| alternate_names     =\n| map_type            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = English Cottage style\n| structural_system   = \n| cost                = \n| location            = [[R\u00e5geleje]]\n| client              = \n| owner               =\n| current_tenants     = \n| landlord            = \n| location_country    = [[Denmark]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|56|6|21.92|N|12|10|42.64|E|type:landmark_region:DK|display=inline,title}}\n| altitude            = \n| start_date          = \n| completion_date     = 1915\n| inauguration_date   = \n| demolition_date     = \n| height              = \n| diameter            = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| floor_count         = \n| floor_area          = \n| main_contractor     = \n| architect           = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| awards              = \n| url                 = \n| references          = \n}}\n'''R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden''' is an [[Arts & Crafts]] inspired country house from 1915 situated on the eastern outskirts of [[R\u00e5geleje]], [[Gribskov Municipality]], some fifty kilometres northwest of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. The house is perched on a small wooded hill, overlooking the  [[Kattegat]] coast. It was listed on