ruary 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Carl and Frethe Glad===\n[[File:R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden vintage photo.jpg|thumb|R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden]]\nThe property was in the beginning of the 1920s acquired by Carl F. Glad (1890-1977) and his wife Grethe Glad (1891-1990). Glad was the owner of L.C. Glad og Co. and appointed as Austrian consul-general in 1921. He planted the property with flowers and other plants from [[Siberia]].  The Glad's lived at [[Store Mariendal]] in [[Hellerup]]. The Glad's belonged to Copenhagen's high society and were often featured in magazines. They covered the distance between Storee Mariendal and R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden in their [[Isotta Fraschini Tipo 8A|Isotta Fraschini Tipo 8A 1925-26]]. Glad was also the owner of a  [[Daimler]]{{dn|date=March 2020}}, [[Bugatti]] and a [[Humber Limited|Humber]].<ref name=\"dvk-database\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dvk-database.dk/bht/bht_1990/bht_1990_101/bht101_1990_38.htm|title=32SG|language=Danish|website=dvk-database.dk|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nGlad's firm went bankrupt in connection with the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|Great Crash of 1929]]. They had to sell both their properties and moved into an apartment in Bredgade. Grethe Glad started the [[Scandinavian Academy of Fashion Design|Margrethe School]] in 1931. After Carl Glad had successfully revived his business a few years later, they were in 1937 able to purchase a property at [[Frederiksholms Kanal]] and to reacquire R\u00e5geg\u00e5rden.<ref name=\"kvinfo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kvinfo.dk/side/597/bio/940/origin/170/|title=Grethe Glad (1891 - 1990)|language=Danish|website=kvinfo.dk|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> Glad was also involved in the Toro Oil Corporation Denmark Limited A/S at [[L\u00f8ve House|Bredgade 76]]. Glad kept the Isotta Fraschini until the early 1970s when  it was then sold to his R\u00e5geleje neighbors Rita and Erik Orth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://veteranbilklub.dk/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/403-VT-januar-2010-lavopl.pdf|titl